<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ920205-0009</DOCNO><DOCID>920205-0009.</DOCID><HL>   Justice Scalia Criticizes   Process of Confirmation</HL><DATE>02/05/92</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><IN>LAW AND LEGAL AFFAIRS (LAW)</IN><NS>LAW andamp; LEGAL ISSUES AND LEGISLATION (LAW)</NS><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)JUSTICE DEPARTMENT (JUS)SUPREME COURT (SUP)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- Supreme Court Justice Antonin Scalia, in anunusual public statement, said the Senate confirmationprocess has become &quot;an absurd spectacle,&quot; with nominees beingsubjected to what he considers to be inappropriateinterrogation about controversial issues of the day.   Although he made passing reference to the stormyconfirmation hearings last fall of Justice Clarence Thomas,Justice Scalia didn't directly link his criticism to theThomas hearings. Justice Scalia spoke last night at a forumhere sponsored by George Washington University.</LP><TEXT>   Justice Scalia devoted most of his talk to the debate overhow to interpret the Constitution. He said the currentcharacter of the confirmation process is an &quot;inevitable&quot;result of an overly expansive view of the rights protected bythe Constitution.</TEXT></DOC>